The best thing is to not worry about it too much for reasons below. And edit what you write before posting it to correct exactly such things. But for the anachronisms and 'too modern' english, just remember
> it's fantasy so there's no reason to be fully loyal to irl past speech conventions
> if you wrote shit set in worlds analogous to irl hundreds or even a thousand years ago, the way people spoke back then, no-one in your 21st century readership would understand what you're posting/writing, so no-one expects you to do that
Instead of worrying about the way people talk fitting into a fictional age, use language to convey their personalities. Give normal inhabitants of villages and towns more colloquial, modern language, save the fantasy english for old-fashioned people, priests, scholars and nobles, and for purposefully silly jesters, theatre actors and things like spirits or gods mocking mortal etiquette, use shakespeare English

Being greentext, you don't really have to follow normal conventions of writing. You should at least try to remember these things
>Keep your tense consistent
>Keep perspective consistent (Is it just one guy focus, several people, etc.)
>Start a new paragraph when someone different speaks, or in this case, a new line
Everything else you can learn along the way. Especially if you ever decide to break into prose.
Anonymous
  • Post
  • Report

Anonymous Mon 10 Jun 2019 11:53:16 No.23658973 Report
Quoted By: >>23659255
>>23658938
Oh, and keep your perspective consistent. 2nd person seems popular in greentext for the self-insert aspect.
In regards to a main character it would go something like this
>1st person: I did the thing.
>2nd person: You did the thing.
>3rd person: He did the thing.
1st is as if the character were telling the story. 2nd is as if the narrator were placing you in the story. 3rd is as if you were an observer watching things pan out, but that doesn't mean you can't have internal thoughts included. I suggest you read up on the perspectives.
